            <tei:div type="commentary" xml:lang="eng" resp="Francesca Murano">
                <tei:note>
                    <tei:p>The inscription consists of the beginning of an alphabetic sequence (10 letters) running around a bronze cylinder. The cylinder is part of a mechanism probably to be intended to distribute sortes (see <tei:ref target="http://zotero.org/groups/2552746/items/IKUTPHDC"><tei:bibl>Crawford, ImIt</tei:bibl></tei:ref>: 1272).</tei:p>
                    <tei:p>The cylinder, open at the back, is closed at the front by a round plaque decorated with the a female bust with her eyes closed, probably the goddess Fortuna. Internally, another bronze cylinder, open at both ends, is applied by means of three brackets. At the base, on the external and internal walls there are ten equidistant and corresponding pairs of square hales (two of them have been filled after a modern intervention) labelled by the letters of the inscription.</tei:p>
                    <tei:p>Letters are used instead of numbers to have the response: sortes were fed into the square holes and distributed out to the enquirers (see <tei:ref target="http://zotero.org/groups/2552746/items/54JCLTPG"><tei:bibl>Maggiani 1994</tei:bibl></tei:ref>.</tei:p>
                </tei:note>
                <tei:note>
                    <tei:p>According to to a different interpretation of the mechanism, it is supposed to have served as rotor of a <tei:ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300036934">cheiroballista</tei:ref>'s winding winch. In this case, the letters would have served as indication of the tension of the elastic part of the propulsor, and therefore of the range. The goddess in the paque would to be identified as Diana. See <tei:ref target="http://zotero.org/groups/2552746/items/CNXW6A77"><tei:bibl>Russo 2004</tei:bibl></tei:ref>: 85-119.</tei:p>
                </tei:note>
            </tei:div>
